# Project: Purchase Request Tracker
# Framework: Streamlit (Python)
# Python version: 3.11+

## Project Context
This is a web app for GIX (University of Washington) to manage
purchase requests. Three user roles: Student (CFO), Instructor,
and Admin (Dorothy). Built with Streamlit + SQLite.

## Coding Standards
- Use Python 3.11+ features and type hints on all functions
- Add Google-style docstrings to all functions
- Use descriptive variable names (no single-letter names)
- Keep functions under 30 lines; extract helpers when needed
- Never hardcode sensitive data (API keys, passwords)

## Streamlit Conventions
- Use st.set_page_config() at the top of the main file
- Use st.cache_data for all database query functions
- Handle errors with try/except and show st.error() or st.warning()
- Never let the app crash on invalid user input

## UI & Branding
- UW purple theme: primary color #4b2e83
- Use st.metric() for all dashboard statistics
- Use Plotly (not Matplotlib or Altair) for all charts
- Always include chart titles, axis labels, and hover tooltips
- If data is empty, show st.info() with a friendly message
  instead of an empty chart

## Database
- SQLite with permanent storage (never delete, only archive)
- Always use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection
- Row objects must be accessed with row["column"] not row.get()

## File Structure
- app.py: Main Streamlit application (single-file architecture)
- purchases.db: SQLite database